<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="business-storytelling">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>comms</group>
    <domain>communicator</domain>
    <summary>Frameworks for structuring persuasive business communication so that audiences grasp the point immediately and remember it. Lead with answer, explain second.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>storytelling</tag>
      <tag>persuasion</tag>
      <tag>presentations</tag>
      <tag>pyramid-principle</tag>
      <tag>scqa</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-29</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Business Storytelling</title>
    <summary>Frameworks for structuring persuasive business communication so that audiences grasp the point immediately and remember it. The three primary structures are: Pyramid Principle (lead with answer, support with MECE arguments), SCQA (Situation-Complication-Question-Answer for narrative tension), and Pixar (causal "because of that" chain for change stories). Core rule: answer first, explain second — busy audiences stop reading the moment their question is answered.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Data alone does not persuade. Studies show people remember stories 22x better than facts. Audiences form judgments in the first 30 seconds; poorly structured presentations lose them before the key point lands. Pyramid Principle structures are the fastest way to ensure decision-makers receive the recommendation before the rationale — the opposite of how most technical people naturally communicate.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Executive summaries, proposals, or recommendation memos</item>
        <item>Presentations where a decision is the outcome</item>
        <item>Case studies and success stories</item>
        <item>Change initiative communications where resistance is expected</item>
        <item>Any written communication longer than 3 paragraphs that needs to persuade</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Exploratory or discovery sessions — narrative tension is not needed when gathering information</item>
        <item>Technical documentation where completeness matters more than persuasion</item>
        <item>Casual updates where no decision is required</item>
        <item>Data reports that are consumed by analysts who want raw structure, not narrative</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="Pyramid Principle">
      <rule>
        <statement>Lead with the main point (the answer), then provide supporting arguments, then evidence — never build up to a conclusion.</statement>
        <rationale>Busy decision-makers stop reading the moment their question is answered. Bottom-up structure (background → argument → conclusion) forces them to read everything before knowing whether to care. Pyramid Principle means they can stop at the headline if it answers their question.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Project proposal using Pyramid Principle">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[MAIN POINT: "We should migrate to cloud infrastructure"

ARGUMENT 1: Cost reduction
  - Evidence: 40% lower TCO analysis
  - Evidence: Competitor benchmarks

ARGUMENT 2: Scalability
  - Evidence: Current capacity limits
  - Evidence: Projected growth

ARGUMENT 3: Speed
  - Evidence: Deployment time comparison
  - Evidence: Developer survey]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="bad" title="Bottom-up structure that buries the recommendation">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA["Current infrastructure has high TCO...
capacity is limited...
deployments take 3 hours...
therefore, we should migrate to cloud."]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="MECE Rule">
      <rule>
        <statement>Arguments supporting the main point must be Mutually Exclusive (no overlap) and Collectively Exhaustive (nothing missing).</statement>
        <rationale>Overlapping arguments confuse the audience about whether you have two reasons or one. Missing arguments leave obvious objections unaddressed, which erodes credibility.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="SCQA Framework">
      <rule>
        <statement>Use SCQA when you need to build narrative tension: Situation (shared context), Complication (what changed or threatens), Question (the logical question that arises), Answer (your solution).</statement>
        <rationale>SCQA works because it mirrors how the audience's mind naturally processes a problem. The Complication creates urgency; the Question creates curiosity; the Answer satisfies both. Pure pyramid without SCQA can feel abrupt in presentations.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Product pitch using SCQA">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[S: "Our team ships 10 features per quarter"
C: "But 30% have critical bugs in the first week"
Q: "How do we maintain velocity while improving quality?"
A: "Automated testing with 80% coverage gate"]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="good" title="Strategy presentation using SCQA">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[S: "We dominate the SMB market with 60% share"
C: "Enterprise represents 5x larger revenue per customer"
Q: "Should we pursue enterprise, and how?"
A: "Phased approach: mid-market first, then enterprise"]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="Pixar Framework">
      <rule>
        <statement>Use the Pixar causal chain for change stories and case studies: each "because of that" link must be a direct consequence of the prior event, not a separate observation.</statement>
        <rationale>The "because of that" connector forces the narrator to establish causality, not just sequence. Without causality, change stories read as coincidences rather than evidence of impact.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Pixar structure applied to a business automation win">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Once upon a time: our team spent 10 hours/week on manual reporting.
Every day: they copy-pasted data between 5 spreadsheets.
One day: we implemented automated dashboards.
Because of that: reporting time dropped to 1 hour.
Because of that: the team focused on analysis, not data entry.
Until finally: we identified $500K in cost savings.]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="Hooks">
      <rule>
        <statement>Open every presentation or document with a hook in the first 30 seconds: use a surprising statistic, a bold contradiction, or a specific story — not an agenda slide.</statement>
        <rationale>Audiences form engagement decisions in the first 30 seconds. An agenda slide answers a question nobody is asking; a hook creates a question the audience wants answered.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Surprising stat: "90% of startups fail. Here's why we won't."</item>
        <item>Question: "What if you could deploy without fear?"</item>
        <item>Bold statement: "Meetings are broken. Let me prove it."</item>
        <item>Story: "Last Tuesday at 2am, our server crashed..."</item>
        <item>Contradiction: "The best code is no code."</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Concrete vs Abstract Language">
      <rule>
        <statement>Replace abstract outcomes with concrete, numbered results. Apply the "so what?" test to every data point: if the implication is not explicit, state it.</statement>
        <rationale>Abstract language ("improved efficiency") is forgettable because it activates no mental image. Concrete numbers anchor understanding and credibility.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="bad">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA["Improved efficiency"
"Better customer experience"
"Enhanced security"]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA["Cut processing time from 4 hours to 15 minutes"
"Reduced support tickets by 60%"
"Blocked 10,000 attacks last month"]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="good" title="The so-what escalation for a reliability metric">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Bad:    "We have 99.9% uptime"
Better: "99.9% uptime means only 8.7 hours of downtime per year"
Best:   "99.9% uptime means your customers never see an error page"]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="Antipatterns and Gotchas">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Burying the main recommendation at the end after extensive background.</description>
        <reason>Decision-makers who stop reading mid-document never receive the recommendation. Lead with the answer per Pyramid Principle.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Ending a presentation without a specific call to action.</description>
        <reason>Vague endings produce "let me think about it" deferrals. A clear ask defines what decision is being requested and when.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <note>Agents will produce Pyramid Principle structures where the three arguments overlap significantly (not MECE); run the MECE checker or explicitly prompt "ensure arguments do not overlap."</note>
      <note>The "Burying the Lead" anti-pattern is the LLM default in long-form writing — agents build up to the conclusion; Pyramid Principle requires inverting this. Explicitly state "lead with the recommendation" in every prompt.</note>
      <note>Hook generation defaults to "Did you know?" or "In today's fast-paced world..." which are both forbidden by professional communication standards; add a negative example list to the hook prompt.</note>
      <note>Pixar framework applied to business without tone calibration produces narrative that feels inappropriately casual in formal settings; specify formality level in the prompt.</note>
      <note>Human checkpoint required: the "So What" annotation must be verified against actual audience knowledge level — an agent calibrated to a general audience will produce over-explained implications for domain experts or under-explained ones for senior executives.</note>
    </section>
    <section name="Agent Usage">
      <p>An agent receives: topic, audience type, key argument, 2-3 supporting data points, desired output format (exec summary / presentation outline / case study). It produces a SCQA narrative scaffold first, then expands into the chosen format using Pyramid Principle structure. A "So What" annotation pass labels each data point with its implication and audience consequence. The hook is generated in 3 variants (stat / question / story) for human selection.</p>
      <p>Recommended subagents: General Claude Opus call — full narrative drafting; Pyramid Principle structure + SCQA requires reasoning about argument hierarchy. General Claude Sonnet call — "So What" annotation pass and case study templating; structured conversion task.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Recommended Prompt Patterns">
      <p>SCQA + Pyramid Principle:</p>
      <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Draft a business narrative for: <TOPIC>.
Audience: <AUDIENCE_TYPE>.
Key recommendation: <ANSWER_FIRST>.
Supporting arguments (3): <ARGUMENT_1>, <ARGUMENT_2>, <ARGUMENT_3>.
Data available: <METRICS>.
Structure: SCQA opening, then Pyramid Principle body (answer → 3 arguments → evidence).
Do not invent metrics. Mark gaps as [DATA NEEDED].]]></code>
      <p>"So What" annotation:</p>
      <code lang="text"><![CDATA[For each data point below, add two levels of "So What":
Level 1: What does this number mean? (implication)
Level 2: Why does this matter to <AUDIENCE>? (consequence)
Data points: <LIST>]]></code>
      <p>Hook generation:</p>
      <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Generate 3 opening hooks for a presentation on: <TOPIC>.
Audience: <AUDIENCE>.
Variant 1: Surprising statistic (must use real data from: <SOURCE_DATA>)
Variant 2: Question (creates genuine tension)
Variant 3: 2-sentence story (specific, not generic)
No clichés. No "In today's world..."]]></code>
    </section>
    <section name="Best Practices">
      <list>
        <item>Write the SCQA Complication before the Answer — if you cannot articulate a genuine tension, the story will not hold; use this as a validity check for the presentation's premise.</item>
        <item>For executive audiences: apply the "So What" test to every data point before finalizing. Executives interpret implications; they do not derive them from raw numbers.</item>
        <item>The "Rule of Three" (three arguments, three supporting facts, three benefits) is not arbitrary — it is the maximum working-memory load for a spoken presentation; enforce it even when more data is available.</item>
        <item>Before/After structure with numbers is the highest-impact single technique in data storytelling; prioritize it over abstract benefit language in every output.</item>
        <item>Use analogies for technical concepts presented to non-technical audiences — the "restaurant kitchen = microservices" example is effective; agents can generate domain-appropriate analogies when given the target audience context.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Limitations and When NOT to Use with Agents">
      <p>Replacing human delivery — storytelling impact depends on speaker presence, timing, and authenticity; a script is a scaffold, not a performance.</p>
      <p>When the data does not exist — agents will invent plausible-sounding numbers to fill the "Concrete vs Abstract" pattern; all quantification must come from real inputs.</p>
      <p>Brand storytelling for external audiences without human review — LLM-generated narrative often lacks the distinctive voice that differentiates a brand.</p>
      <p>When the "Complication" in SCQA is unclear — forcing narrative tension around a non-problem produces manipulative-feeling content.</p>
      <p>Pyramid Principle requires MECE (Mutually Exclusive, Collectively Exhaustive) argument structure — agents frequently produce overlapping arguments or miss a category.</p>
      <p>Pixar framework applied to business contexts can feel forced ("once upon a time, our team...") without careful tone calibration.</p>
      <p>The "Concrete vs Abstract" conversion requires real metrics; agents will generate plausible but false benchmarks if not constrained.</p>
      <p>Hook generation tends toward cliche — "Did you know that X% of [category]?" is LLM default; force specificity via prompt constraints.</p>
      <p>Long presentations (10+ slides) lose structural coherence because agents optimize locally per slide rather than globally.</p>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/executive-summary.txt" purpose="Pyramid-structured executive summary: Recommendation / Context / Key Points / Next Steps"/>
      <template path="templates/case-study.txt" purpose="Challenge / Solution / Results / Quote case study structure"/>
      <template path="templates/presentation-outline.txt" purpose="4-section presentation: Hook / Problem / Solution / Call to Action"/>
    </templates>
